rity groups, social science experiments with minority adults, content analyses of newspapers and congressional archives, and in-depth interviews with minority individuals, Pérez makes two key points. First, a person of color's identity does exist, and we can reliably measure it, as well as distinguish it from other identities that minorities hold. Second, across a wide swath of circumstances, identifying as a person of color profoundly shapes how minorities view themselves and their political system. Diversity’s Child is a vital and engaging look at America’s identity politics as well as at how people of color think about racial disparities and how politics can best solve them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aGroup identityzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aIdentity politicszUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aPolitical psychologyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamerica, bipoc, demographic, disparities, groups, identifying, identity, individuals, interviews, majority, minorities, minority, opinion, outlook, political, population, racial, ramifications, science, social, states, unify, united, voters, whites, race.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226799933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226799933/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles